segments.text: and reared in... Tell me your name, four names first.
Charles L. Bowie, the old Y.D.
Bowie.
Born and reared in Grandview, Texas, a small agricultural community south of Ford.
Completed a high school education there in 1939.
and attended Hillsborough Junior College one year.
You know, Matt, were you active in 4-H, etc.?
Active in vocational agriculture, which there wasn't a 4-H in that community, but vocational ag school gave you then agricultural projects, or animal projects, and sports, athletics.
Well, after going one year to Hillsborough Junior College, I
Attended two years at North Texas Agricultural College in Arlington.
A major in general agriculture and had a little husband, Rick.
Now, they were under A&M affiliation at that time?
Yeah, that was a branch of Texas A&M at that time.
And before we became UTA, we became UTA after I came here.
Then transferred to Texas A&M.
Excuse me, I remember Tom Harrington saying that was one of the biggest mistakes we ever made, letting that go.
Oh, I can believe that.
And he would have moved the system office.
He said, that really shocked me.
This was 20 years ago, you know.
Well, it went to Dallas, you know.
They've got a real university up there now.
Yeah.
Excuse me.
They were smaller then.
Of course, at that time, they had a good ROTC, which you could get an advanced contract.
You could make the basic there, you could get an advanced contract.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
So I transferred there.
I came here after completing two years there.
Came to Texas A&M in 1942.
Graduated in 1945 in veterinary medicine.
I guess the thing that influenced me most to pursue a career in veterinary medicine, we operated a dairy.
And in the TB eradication program, Dr. Leon Cloud, Leon G. Cloud,
came down and tested the herd.
He was driving a new black Hudson Terraplane coupe with a portable radio.
I can still see that case.
Battery-operated portable radio.
This was about 1936, I guess.
I thought, and he wore, he had a little old cap, as I remember, white cap in the building, like he's a sports car guy.
I thought, boy, that must be alive.
For a rural kiddo, that's got to be the greatest.
It's amazing how little things like that influence you all.
everybody somewhere along the way.
Also Dr. Allman I met quite early and Dr. Burns in Cleveland by doing the veterinary practice for us.

I can remember having gone forward Dr. Allman had been in practice in Itasca, Texas and there was a veterinarian I don't call his name at the moment he died and his wife was still operating the hospital there on South Main in Fort Worth
I believe it was him and the mercy cat and dog, I suppose.
But anyway, I went up to pick up some cowpox salve that Dr. Allman mixed up in medication.
I must have been about 16 then.
Drove the car up there by myself and got that and had a big day.
Again, a country boy in town.
But Dr. Allman, Dr. Burns, I remember Dr. Burns, his influence on my idea of maintaining a professional image.
He officed in the back of a drug store west side of the square in Cleaver.
And he had a coat rack in there and he always had a suit on and a tie.
And he'd hang his coat back, coat on the rack, sit in a swivel chair and visit with the clients and talk to them about the name.
But he never made a call without putting that coat on, hot or cold, whatever.
He wore a suit all the time.
He said they don't expect you to slop the hogs and stretch barbed wire if you wear a suit.
He was an A&M graduate in animal science, animal husbandry, but he was an Ohio State graduate in veterinary medicine.
He was from Cuero.
He was a cousin of Patton W. Burns, who was head of Pharmacology College here.
And he was on the board of examiners when I took the exam for the state board of licenses.
Arthur Clayton.
And when you received your degree in 45, what did you do?
Did you go into practice?
I had borrowed money, federal money, to finish up on senior year.
And I went to work for the City of Houston Health Board.
I worked there two years until I got my bills paid.
Went back to the old hometown, which I don't always highly advocate.
And went in to practice there and remained there for 17 years until I came to the College of Under Medicine.
Now your hometown again was... Grandview.
Grandview, yeah.
I had no intention of going into academia at all.
I was planning to do something else, perhaps go with another practitioner where we'd have a little free time.
It was pretty confining.
And I attended the TVMA meeting in San Antonio.
and sat down with Bill Romaine, Nick Callaham, Al Price, their wives, and my wife and I.
And they said they were looking for somebody in the clinic, Dr. Young, and he got signed on for a two-year stint in Pakistan.
And I said, no way I can handle that.
I'm just an old rural practitioner.
I couldn't do that.
But I would love to be in an environment where I have the...
availability of consultation on problem cases, better laboratory facilities, and better diagnostic exposure.

So as we'll come down and see us, time passed, and Jim Denton, who is now deceased, but Jim was a classmate and an ambulatory clinician here, he and his wife drove up one Sunday, came down to the hospital there, and I was washing OB chains and dirty buckets by myself.
He talked to me a while and said, well just come down and look at it.
So sure, I came down and they convinced me that I could work in the program and pursue a master's degree.
Under those circumstances, it was a great reluctance, I came down.
What year was that?
I came in March of 1964.
Okay, we'll come back to all that in your practice in a minute.
Elmo, how did you get into this business?
So forth.
By osmosis, I guess.
I don't know.
Is it Elmo?
E-L-M-O.
My first name is Walter.
Okay.
My father's name was also Walter, so I was called throughout my life by my middle name, Elmo.
I was formed.
born and raised in the Lower Rio Grande Valley, a little community called Ed Couch.
Ed Couch?
Ed Couch, E-D-C-O-U-C-H. One word?
Named after a Mr. Couch who owned the town side of Ed Couch before it became a town.
And of course his first name was Ed, so they named the community after him.
My dad was
involved in farming a lot of the land that eventually became the community of Edcouch.
And during high school, we had a young man that came in, a graduate of Texas A&I, that was an ag teacher.
And he started off with a 4-H class, and then when I got into high school, I was
part of the vocational agriculture class.
And our livestock activity was most appealing to me in that, more so than the farming aspects of vocational agriculture.
And I probably got to do more than my share of castrations and deep warnings and such as that by default.
Oh yeah, I said.
The ag classes would go out to the different farms and communities around
kind of a dearth of veterinarians around that area at the time.
And so ag class did an awful lot of castrations, and caponizing, and dehorning, and vaccinating, and all sort of activity of that nature.
And I thoroughly enjoyed it.
And on part of the default on many of the others in the class, well, I got to do more than my share of it.
And I think that that was probably about as influential as any other one thing.

my deciding to be a veterinarian my ag teacher at one time assigned the class the responsibility of making the report to the class on the attributes of a profession and at that point in time i chose to talk on veterinary medicine as a profession
I also had an uncle that was a veterinarian.
He was not a graduate of a veterinary college.
He'd attended the Dallas Veterinary School.
And I think Rutherford was instrumental in promoting and maintaining a lot of that schooling.
And when he was a licensed veterinarian, as a result of the grandfather clause and the
practiced as a veterinarian at the time for a number of years and was granted a license under the grandfather clause.

He really didn't have a whole lot of influence on my decision to become a veterinarian except that I thought that if I had an uncle who was a veterinarian it might be all right for me too, but I think my ag teacher and my activities in agricultural class was probably more instrumental in my decision.
So how'd you get to Texas A&M?
Well, I guess.
I guess as a result of my making the talk on veterinary medicine as a profession, I actually talked myself into it and investigated the economics of it and such as that.
I came to A&M then.
I was a fish and well I graduated from high school in 1941, came up here in September of 41.
Three days after I graduated from high school, I hitchhiked to A&M to try to locate it, find a job and came up here and visited with Mr. Horsley in the employment office and
course he made no promises whatsoever.

I was probably doubting that I would ever show up as a student at A&M, but I made the initial contact with him and when I came back in September, I renewed acquaintances with Mr. Horsley and he put my name on the list and said, don't call me, I'll call you when you have something.
This was a matter of hitchhiking, goes up here and back, which I continued to do throughout the time I was in school.
I hitchhiked back and forth every time.
That's a pretty good hitchhiker.
Four occasions.
Did you have to spend many nights out on the way?
Back and forth.
Did you have to spend many nights out on the way?
I spent as long as over 24 hours.
I bet.
hitchhiking up here, and I've done it in less than eight hours, which is good times, hitchhiking, coming by way of Austin and Round Rock and Hearn and then back down to College Station.
Made the acquaintance rather quickly of Dr. Marsteller, who knew my uncle,
But I don't really think he admired my uncle extremely, my uncle not being a graduate veterinarian, but a licensed veterinarian.
And I don't know whether this had a role to play in his judging my uncle's quarter horses down in a horse show in Mesquite, Texas.
The year before, my uncle had both the champion mare and stallion.
quarter horses, Palomino quarter horses at the State Fair in Dallas, and just about eight months later took him to a horse show over at Mesquite.
Dr. Marshfeller was the judge at that show, and he didn't place.
My uncle had claimed the animosity that Dr. Marshfeller had for judging his horses down, but
None of this rubbed off on Dr. Markenteller as far as his attitude toward me was concerned.
I had nothing but high regard and held him in high esteem.
I struggled through my first year and failed chemistry, so that put me one year behind graduating.
You don't pass chemistry, you don't start physiology, so then starting my sophomore year,
I had a job working at the Shulman Theaters in Bryan.
This would go on three nights a week, would go on for about one o'clock in the morning.
The changing marquee and such as that took extra time.
Well, the first grade report came out, and it was obvious to me that I was in trouble, and it was also obvious to Dr. Marsteller.
He took a personal interest in each and every individual student, I believe.
I don't think he treated me any differently than anyone else.
He called me into his office and sat me down over there and said, Mr. Crenshaw, it seems that you're having some problems with your grades.
Well, I don't know how to describe Dr. Marsteller's voice, but it was kind of a grunting dissertation and somewhat of a nasal twang at the same time.

I told him, yes, I realize that, and he wanted to know if I had an explanation for it, and of course I had an explanation for it, working till 1 or 1.30 in the morning, three nights a week, and going out, living in the basement of one of the old, old homes in Bryan at the time, and there was about six boys living in the basement of that old home, and I'd go home at 1.30 in the morning, and
decide I was going to study, and needless to say, about 10 to 15 minutes, and I'd be nodding and pointless to make any further efforts.
And I'd say, well, I'll get up early in the morning and study.
This never happened.
I'd be late catching a bus from Bryan to campus to make it to class.
So he persuaded me that I'd better discontinue my work at the Shulman Theater.
So post haste, I resigned my position there.
imposed further upon Mr. Hartsby to find a job on campus, which wound up being in the Landscape Arts Department.
Which was kind of a deceiving thing, also.
He told me, you go over to that red building over there next to the laundry, and says,
I asked for a certain individual.
I don't recall his name now.
I said, you go into that building.
I said, he'll find a job for you.
I had visions of grandeur on my way over to this red building next to the laundry.
Landscape art.
I envisioned myself working at a table and designing flower beds and working with this shrub and that tree and such and that.
And I walked into the red building next to the laundry, and there was nothing in there but
Grubbing holes, shovels, axes, wheelbarrows.
It suddenly hits you, right?
And then on Saturday afternoons, of course, there were very few people working in the landscape arts department.
About three of us showed up for work Saturday afternoon.
This was during the time that football was being played, and I was an avid football fan even at that point in time.
I would be standing there washing pots, and you could hear the screams coming from Kyle's field.
It was hard.
It was pretty tough.
I'd been working for 35 cents an hour and missing a football game.
But one thing led to another, and I wound up with a better job after that.
And your grades picked up?
My grades picked up, needless to say.
I managed to stay in school, thanks to Dr. Marsteller.
So that's about my transition from a farm boy to the College of Veterinary Medicine.
And you got your degree when?
In 46.
February 46.
And then what did you do with that degree?
Well, let's see.
You had to fill in on the Army Specialized Training Program and enroll in veterinary medicine.
Charlie and I both were.
participating in the Army Specialized Training Program.
That lasted for only one year, and those of us that were not near enough graduation were given reserve officer's commission.
Given the M.A.C., Medical Administrative.
The Medical Administrative Corps, classified as second lieutenants, and were permitted to finish veterinary school.
Now you technically never were under the G.I.
Bill as such.
No.
This was that special training program.
The G.I.
Bill didn't come into being until after World War II and quite some time after, wasn't it Charlie?
I don't think it was.
I don't remember either.
I was thinking 47, 48.
About 48, 49, one old building.
When the impact really hit.
And they had some of that at the air basement, some on campus.
The organized return of the bedroom was good on the Hazelwood building.
That's the thing you're talking about, GI building.
Yeah, right.
Yeah, Hazelwood building.
I checked that day.
I never thought about it.
I was thinking it was about 47, 48 at least.
Yeah, probably so.
Well, this thing was a deal that you entered as a private when we went to Fort Sam and then after spending a month over there close on the railroad route, we were sent back here.
They had a Marine Corps and a Navy.
Air Corps.
Air Corps.
Medics, yeah.
Specialized on specialized training.
Lived over in the new area.
Don't hate nothing at all.
As a result of the Speed Up program, going summers and all, they had three graduating classes a year.
In 46, we graduated three classes.
I called myself a member of the advanced class in 46.
I finished February the 2nd of 46, and there was a graduating class in June and one in August.
four to six, retarded classes.
And at that time, graduation, well, I joined my uncle and Dan Beckley, who had graduated about three years before me.
It was with my uncle in ,, Texas.
OK, so you went in practice with this uncle that you had?
Yeah, with my non-graduate but licensed veterinarian uncle.
Hillary Crenshaw.
At Garland?
At Garland.

He had a booming large animal practice and just a piddling bit of small animal practice, which we conducted, the surgery we did, we did in a cheap metal garage that backed the wagons or trailers or whatever out of the garage and had a little surgery table set up in there.
That's where we did our small animal practice.
And he still had his Palomino Quarter horses and they were fine animals that provided me my introduction to artificial insemination, I guess.
It just thrilled him when he had two mares come in at one time for breeding to his stag.
He'd breed one mare and he'd take a gelatin capsule and go in and harvest a portion of the semen that had been ejaculated in the vagina of the mare and implant the
and another mayor.
That's surprisingly good.
Is that right?
Was that being done commonly, or is that something he picked up?
I don't know how commonly it was being done.
I don't remember he got the idea, but he was doing it quite commonly.
This old stallion was pretty popular, and you were getting a lot of calls for service to it.
Ptoleminos were popular at that time, and quarter horses were popular, gaining popularity.

Yeah, and artificial insemination just coming along, because I had a dairy cow heifer, and we used to get people up from LSU to come inseminate the cow, because she was such a terror anyway with the bull.
But it was apparently kind of a novel thing at the time.
So you were in practice in Garland, and you're still heavily large animal.
Heavily large animal.
Right.
And I really enjoyed the large animal work.
I really had very little introduction to small animal.
Back in school, we had very little.
That was the right next question.
Both of you, when you were here, was there any emphasis at all on small animal or sort of incidental?
I would say no emphasis.
What did you say?
It was just available whenever we came in.
You know, as students, there weren't any dogs.
All dogs were neutered three miles from the campus.
But there were students who could catch one running free.
That was an opportunity to spay or cast or anything.
If we were in my office, I'd show you a book that was really our only textbook in small animal, dogs and cats.
And it's just about that thick.
And it's a well-worn book.
I'm going to get the time of that.
I'll tell you before I leave.
Don't even forget it.
Because that's good.
And, of course, now... Is that Brumley's?
Yeah.
Is that Brumley's?
Would you like me to go get that now while you're making your note here on that?
Okay.
All right.
Yeah, because those kind of pieces of information are pretty good to have.
Because one thing I know I picked up in the veterinary chapter, medicine chapter I did at A&M, were the three or four titles of books.
And there just wasn't much, you know, when Francis came in from the 30th century.
I came back...
I came back in the summer.
We had a mid-summer conference, a mid-year conference.
We called it the June conference.
We met at the MSC on campus.
And I remember buying a poetry pathology book, Beasters.
Oh, it was about that thick.
It was tremendous.
The book that we had was a bartered card.
It was about this thick, about in that big square, I think.
And Banks, Dr. Banks, used to laugh about, well, there were only five diseases of poultry when we were in school.
Yeah, probably so.
Yeah, now you've got everything in the world.
Root, collar, bubble foot.
We really got more in poultry than we did in small animals, dogs and cats.
I wouldn't be surprised, yeah, commercial, because Folter would have been heavily commercial-wise already.
That's right.
It was a plot treatment deal.
I've always, of course I'm a book person anyway, but I've always been intrigued by the textbook things.
There was one on the horse, somebody on the horse, it was a classic.
I went to the library, we had it in the library, in fact, 1880 vintage thing, and apparently it was still used in the 20th century.
Well, Keeping Livestock Healthy in 1942 was about the biggest general book we had.
Do you remember?
You wrote your representative who got that one.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Old E. Butler called me one day when he was going to testify on Bruce Loveson for Comedian Austin.
I can't find my Keeping Livestock Healthy book.
I want to borrow yours.
Well, they put that out annually for many years.
Oh, yeah.
I got one about four years ago.
It had even colored plates in it.
Then they had one on the diseases of the horse and the diseases of cattle.
Those were two broken down bodies after that 40 years.
I used to have clients that would want me to get them books on diseases of cattle.
Always.
And I'd tell them about keeping livestock healthy.
That was a constant.
And where's a good book I can get them?
I don't know.
I had one that pestered me about that.
A young man, he was college educated, kept pestering me about books.
And I finally gave him my book on the diseases of cattle, the Saunders publication.
And he took that thing home.
He brought it back in about a week, something like that.
He always smoked a cigar.
And he walked into that cigar in the mouth and said, keep that damn thing.
He said, everything in there sounds alike.
So how long were you in practice now at Garland?
Well, I practiced there for 10 months, and for some reason Uncle Sam thought that as a result of my year in the Army Specialized Training Program that I still owed them some time as a veterinarian.
So I thought they were bluffing.
They sent me an opportunity to sign up as a...
That's what they were going in as at that time.
And I declined.
Then I got a draft notice and time to report.
So I post-haste went into Dallas and made application to enter as an officer in the veterinary corps.
That was close.
And the day I was to report for my physical for the draft, my commission came through in the veterinary corps.
So I was being like C.K.
Jones, who did time as a buck private in Fort Sam Houston, Texas, and he can tell you some wild stories about that.
Of course, being a Texas A&M graduate, he was well-versed in treatment of equine diseases, horses and mules, and they had quite a contingent of mules down there in particular.
And the veterinarians on duty at Fort Brown were all from the northeast and they didn't know anything about it.
They'd bring a mule into the clinic there and ask to see case.
I guess they called him private.
I think he was first class.
Did he make first class?
I don't know.
I haven't heard this story.
Ask him.
What's wrong with this mule for $54 a month?
I don't know what the hell happened to that mule.
Turn around and walk off.
You know how independent he was.
It still is.
So how long were you in service now?
Well, I was in two years.
Okay.
And your station?
Well, I spent about...
three months at Chicago, two months in Chicago, I guess.
And most of the people that went in to Chicago went through their meat and dairy hygiene school.
I didn't have that opportunity.
They had officers at Fort Sill, Oklahoma that were being mustered out and had a colonel there that

I was rather impatient to have some officers underneath him, you know, do the paperwork and running around the meat inspection and all that sort of thing, so they cut me some orders to go to Fort Sill instead of going to the meat and dairy hygiene school.
In some ways, a major in Chicago lost my orders.
and were later found on his desk and had been there for just about five weeks.
So I was five weeks late getting to Fort Selle, Oklahoma, just bumming around in the Quartermaster Corps offices up there and such as that, reported to a very irate colonel at Lawton, Oklahoma.
And he took me down to the, well, the first afternoon I got in there, we immediately went down to this cooler for the Quartermaster Corps
he took me in the cooler there and wanted me to tell him which of these is a steer carcass and which is a heifer carcass and I had no idea.
I couldn't even tell male from a female carcass and he was just furious.
I mean he was rabid.
Colonel Wiseman,
They sent him a greenhorn like that.
You couldn't tell a male from a female.
I knew nothing about looking for the pizzle eye to distinguish.
This was where the penis muscle, the retractor muscle of the penis attached on the pelvis.
There was no distinction between male and female carcass.
No one told me anything about that.
Did we have that in school Charlie?
Did I miss that?
No, no.
But anyway, I was at Fort Sill for about six months, I guess, and then they transferred me to Fort Sam in San Antonio.
And I was doing most of the meat inspection work.
Well, at Fort Sill, I also was involved in the small animal clinic that rendered veterinary services to
military personnel in the Lofton area.
That provided me really my first exposure to small animal medicine.
And it was very interesting.
I found it really intriguing.
We had a nice clinic set up there.
And then when I went to Fort Sam, we had a real nice veterinary clinic there where we treated both large and small animals.
It had an awful lot of horses.
at Fort Sam.
And one of my most interesting experiences there involved Colonel Wainwright, Skinny Wainwright, the Death March.
He was there at the Fourth Army headquarters in San Antonio, and he had about four of his jumping horses that he kept on the post there.
Of course, we saw about their health needs at the veterinary clinic.
And they called us one morning about his favorite jumping horse, Once Again was his name, having colic.
And I went out and encountered the sergeant that was presenting him with his colic.
Colonel Wyatt, who was commanding officer of 4th Army Headquarters at the time, and was head of the post hospital, veterinary hospital, he came out and took over Mr. Kenny Wainwright's horse.
He thought that most colling cases are rather simple to treat, and some of them even self-resolving, but boy, if they're not, you've got really trouble on your hands.
Well, fortunately for me, Colonel White took over.
And needless to say, the bottom line, General Wainwright's horse once again became never more.
Oh, boy.
I'm so glad for you.
So that was another close call you had there.
Somebody's looking over me, I guess.
Okay, then how did you, excuse me, go ahead.
Well, I guess while I was at Fort Sam, I came in, well, I attended the local veterinary meetings, which enabled me to see a real transition in organized veterinary medicine, I guess.
Of course, we'd just been through the war years.
I'd go to the San Antonio or Bexar County Veterinary Association meeting, and there wouldn't be maybe five or six veterinarians there.
Looking around San Antonio, it looked attractive to my wife and I, and I was scouting it out as a potential site to practice after getting out of the service.

I actually located a boarding kennel that they had for sale, a real nice facility, and I saw this as having potential to be converted into a veterinary clinic and hospitalizing facilities with the warrants and cages and runs that they have there.
But we had our first child born there.
The baby was 13 days old.
My wife died from a spinal injection.
It was kind of a real fiasco in the medical profession, I guess.
It was kind of an enlightening thing that you could encounter mistakes and mishaps
in the medical field.
I may be a little prouder of the veterinary profession, but individuals are all going to make mistakes in regards to what they're training in the field that they're in.
But as a result of that, my mother was just real anxious to raise my baby, so she came up and took my baby home to Westwood, to Ed Couch, actually.
And I had about another six months to do,
in the service before I was discharged.
And so when I was discharged, I went back to the Valley and started to practice in Washington, Texas.
So that's how I wound up back at home doing practice.
I'd always heard in school that it's not wise to go back to your hometown and practice with your friends or the factory service.
You'd always be little Elmo and lack the respect that you might have if you were in the new community and starting over fresh and all that.
But I didn't find that to be true.
I found my friends being very receptive to me as a veterinarian.
And I don't think any of them expected free service or anything of that nature.
I think I might have been somewhat of a humanitarian.
I never charged exorbitant fees.
I think my fees were always very reasonable, I guess.
I kind of operated on the philosophy of get them for a dollar many times instead of ten dollars once or something.
I did practice at a reasonable fee.
One thing that might have influenced that, there was a practitioner at Westaco that, while I was growing up,
Much better businessman than I was, I guess.
He got really exorbitant fees for a lot of his services, but really didn't render a whole lot of service.
And this made the climate there very good for me as a new veterinarian in the community.
Just be on the job, render good service, and collect reasonable fees.
I know I've raised this question several times in some other conversations about how do you decide what kind of feed
or to charge, and there's no good answer, I gather.
Well, no, it depends a lot on the clientele, where you are and what, of course, the Rio Grande Valley has never been populated with a lot of wealthy people or even well-to-do people.
It's kind of a poverty area.
At the present time, there's about 28% unemployment in the valley area.
And those people have pay-ups, and they need veterinary services, so that has an influence on what some of your charges might be.
But I practice some socialized veterinary medicine to an extent.
I charge more for people that I thought could afford it.
I'd look out in the parking lot and see what they were riding around in.
But I never had anyone throw my hand at me.
So how long were you in practice now?
22 years.
22 years.
OK, so both of you really had a long private practice before you came into academia.
I didn't realize how many people change at 17 years.
That's interesting.
I met those people that came here to the faculty and others.
In about 15, 17 years, you do something.
That's interesting.
Now, how did you make that transition?
And then let's go back to your practice days, Anthony.
I don't know.
I had, I think, as good a mixed practice as it was in the state of Texas, and I enjoyed it thoroughly.

And about three years before I came up here, I bought an excellent piece of property just halfway between West Dakota and Mercedes at the intersection of the main highway up and down the valley and a road that goes down to Mexico.
and remodeled this furniture showroom that had been vacant for probably 12, 15 years.
And I bought it worth the price and remodeled it for a mixed practice at facilities for large and small animals, both all under one roof.
And I had, I think, an unusual large animal practice.
Probably 75% of my large animal practice was made up of registered Charolais cattle.
And during the years that I was in practice there, value escalated to the point that I think it was ridiculous that some of the prices they were getting for it.
I had some terrible $50,000 cows in my practice.
